{"parse":{"title":"Language on Vacation","pageid":44137187,"revid":810268034,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">Language on Vacation: An Olio of Orthographical Oddities <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Language+on+Vacation%3A+An+Olio+of+Orthographical+Oddities&amp;rft.author=%5B%5BDmitri+Borgmann%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BCharles+Scribner%27s+Sons%5D%5D&amp;rft.pages=318&amp;rft_id=info:oclcnum/8478220\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Language_on_Vacation.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Language on Vacation.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e2/Language_on_Vacation.jpg/220px-Language_on_Vacation.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"321\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/e/e2/Language_on_Vacation.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"237\" data-file-height=\"346\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Dmitri_Borgmann\" title=\"Dmitri Borgmann\">Dmitri Borgmann</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Country</th><td>\nUnited States</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\nEnglish</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Published</th><td>\n1965</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Scribner%27s_Sons\" title=\"Charles Scribner&#39;s Sons\">Charles Scribner's Sons</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Media&#160;type</th><td>\nPrint</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Pages</th><td>\n318</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/OCLC#Identifiers_and_linked_data\" title=\"OCLC\"><abbr title=\"Online Computer Library Center number\">OCLC</abbr></a></th><td>\n<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/8478220\">8478220</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Followed&#160;by</th><td>\n<i><a href=\"/wiki/Beyond_Language:_Adventures_in_Word_and_Thought\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Beyond Language: Adventures in Word and Thought\">Beyond Language: Adventures in Word and Thought</a></i></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>Language on Vacation: An Olio of Orthographical Oddities</b></i> is a 1965 book written by <a href=\"/wiki/Dmitri_Borgmann\" title=\"Dmitri Borgmann\">Dmitri Borgmann</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Content\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Content</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Reception_and_legacy\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reception and legacy</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Production_history\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Production history</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Content\">Content</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Language_on_Vacation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Content\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Borgmann introduces his book by stating that he hopes it will \"elevate <a href=\"/wiki/Recreational_linguistics\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Recreational linguistics\">recreational linguistics</a> to the same high level of esteem now enjoyed by <a href=\"/wiki/Recreational_mathematics\" title=\"Recreational mathematics\">recreational mathematics</a>\" and will cultivate in the reader an awareness of the beauty of words.  Chapter by chapter, the book goes on to describe and provide examples of long-established forms of letter-play, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Palindrome\" title=\"Palindrome\">palindromes</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Word_reversal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Word reversal\">reversals</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Antigram\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Antigram\">antigrams</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Anagram\" title=\"Anagram\">anagrams</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Pangram\" title=\"Pangram\">pangrams</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Transposition_cipher\" title=\"Transposition cipher\">transpositions</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Word_square\" title=\"Word square\">word squares</a>.  Also included are chapters on word-level phenomena, such as sentence palindromes, and wordplay involving <a href=\"/wiki/Arithmetic_progression\" title=\"Arithmetic progression\">arithmetic</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Geometric_progression\" title=\"Geometric progression\">geometric progressions</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Piphilology\" title=\"Piphilology\">Piphilology</a> and various methods of encoding the digits of <a href=\"/wiki/Pi\" title=\"Pi\">pi</a> into word <a href=\"/wiki/Mnemonics\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mnemonics\">mnemonics</a> are also discussed.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reception_and_legacy\">Reception and legacy</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Language_on_Vacation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Reception and legacy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>On publication the book attracted favourable reviews, with <i><a href=\"/wiki/Time_(magazine)\" title=\"Time (magazine)\">Time</a></i> calling it \"one of the year's most peculiar and fascinating books\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-time_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-time-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Kirkus_Reviews\" title=\"Kirkus Reviews\">Kirkus Reviews</a></i> summarizing it as \"intellectual busy work which is fine entertainment\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-kirkus_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kirkus-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Scientific_American\" title=\"Scientific American\">Scientific American</a></i>'s <a href=\"/wiki/James_R._Newman\" title=\"James R. Newman\">James R. Newman</a>'s lauding it as \"the best, most comprehensive book ever written on\u2026 recreational linguistics\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-newman_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-newman-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  Later writers have come to regard the book as \"groundbreaking\", noting that it was the first book devoted solely to the description and study of wordplay, rather than simply providing a list of puzzles.<sup id=\"cite_ref-malkiel_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-malkiel-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-father_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-father-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-evans_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-evans-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-apocrypha_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-apocrypha-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The book is notable for having introduced and popularized the use of the word <i><a href=\"/wiki/Logology\" title=\"Logology\">logology</a></i> to mean <a href=\"/wiki/Recreational_linguistics\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Recreational linguistics\">recreational linguistics</a>, or the study and practice of <a href=\"/wiki/Wordplay\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wordplay\">wordplay</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-evans_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-evans-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-johnson_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-johnson-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>  Borgmann has since been referred to as the \"Father of Logology\" and his book is credited with ushering in a \"golden age of wordplay\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-father_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-father-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-evans_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-evans-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-morice_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-morice-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>  The book's publicity led to Borgmann being contracted by industrial design firm <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Loewy_%26_Snaith&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Loewy &amp; Snaith (page does not exist)\">Loewy &amp; Snaith</a> to invent brand names for its client <a href=\"/wiki/Standard_Oil\" title=\"Standard Oil\">Standard Oil</a>, and to <a href=\"/wiki/Greenwood_Periodicals\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Greenwood Periodicals\">Greenwood Periodicals</a> selecting him to establish and edit their logology journal, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Word_Ways\" title=\"Word Ways\">Word Ways</a></i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-father_5-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-father-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-baechler_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-baechler-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Production_history\">Production history</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Language_on_Vacation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Production history\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Language on Vacation</i> was published in 1965 by <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Scribner%27s_Sons\" title=\"Charles Scribner&#39;s Sons\">Charles Scribner's Sons</a>; recreational mathematician <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Madachy\" title=\"Joseph Madachy\">Joseph Madachy</a> served as the author's <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_agent\" title=\"Literary agent\">literary agent</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-omni_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-omni-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>  The book went through at least two printings, but as of  2005<sup class=\"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update\" style=\"display:none;\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Language_on_Vacation&amp;action=edit\">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup> it was out of print.<sup id=\"cite_ref-apocrypha_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-apocrypha-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-damn_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-damn-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>  The manuscript Borgmann originally submitted contained two additional chapters, on word play involving <a href=\"/wiki/Phonetic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Phonetic\">phonetics</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Semantic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Semantic\">semantics</a>, which were rejected by the publisher.  Some of this material was recycled for Borgmann's second book, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Beyond_Language:_Adventures_in_Word_and_Thought\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Beyond Language: Adventures in Word and Thought\">Beyond Language: Adventures in Word and Thought</a></i>, and other topics were worked into <i>Word Ways</i> articles.<sup id=\"cite_ref-apocrypha_7-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-apocrypha-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Language_on_Vacation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-time-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-time_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,842150,00.html\">\"Word salad\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/TIME\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"TIME\">TIME</a></i>. <b>86</b> (12): 139. September 17, 1965.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=TIME&amp;rft.atitle=Word+salad&amp;rft.volume=86&amp;rft.issue=12&amp;rft.pages=139&amp;rft.date=1965-09-17&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcontent.time.com%2Ftime%2Fmagazine%2Farticle%2F0%2C9171%2C842150%2C00.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALanguage+on+Vacation\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-kirkus-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-kirkus_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/dmitri-a-borgmann/language-on-vacation/\">\"Language on Vacation\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Kirkus_Reviews\" title=\"Kirkus Reviews\">Kirkus Reviews</a></i>. August 19, 1965.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Kirkus+Reviews&amp;rft.atitle=Language+on+Vacation&amp;rft.date=1965-08-19&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.kirkusreviews.com%2Fbook-reviews%2Fdmitri-a-borgmann%2Flanguage-on-vacation%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALanguage+on+Vacation\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-newman-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-newman_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a href=\"/wiki/James_R._Newman\" title=\"James R. Newman\">Newman, James R.</a> (December 1965). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nature.com/scientificamerican/journal/v213/n6/pdf/scientificamerican1265-114.pdf\">\"Books\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Scientific_American\" title=\"Scientific American\">Scientific American</a></i>. <b>213</b>: 114\u2013121. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1038/scientificamerican1265-114\">10.1038/scientificamerican1265-114</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Scientific+American&amp;rft.atitle=Books&amp;rft.volume=213&amp;rft.pages=114-121&amp;rft.date=1965-12&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1038%2Fscientificamerican1265-114&amp;rft.aulast=Newman&amp;rft.aufirst=James+R.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Fscientificamerican%2Fjournal%2Fv213%2Fn6%2Fpdf%2Fscientificamerican1265-114.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALanguage+on+Vacation\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-malkiel-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-malkiel_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Yakov_Malkiel\" title=\"Yakov Malkiel\">Malkiel, Yakov</a> (1968). <i>Essays on Linguistic Themes</i>. University of California Press. p.&#160;392.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Essays+on+Linguistic+Themes&amp;rft.pages=392&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft.date=1968&amp;rft.aulast=Malkiel&amp;rft.aufirst=Yakov&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALanguage+on+Vacation\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-father-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-fat